{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:14:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:14:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/641"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.04,0.17,0.09,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54234"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/641"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39711"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2280"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54234"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after attending her general practice earlier in the day with some right-sided pleuritic chest pain and dyspnoea. The previous day her chiropractor had done dry needling for back pain. Her doctor ordered a chest X-ray (image) and on the basis of the findings, referred the patient to the hospital. The patient is otherwise well and her symptoms have now resolved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit to hospital for observation","Aspirate under CT guidance","Insert an intercostal drain and admit to hospital","Insert a Heimlich valve and review the following day","Insert a Heimlich valve and admit to hospital"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a small right-sided pneumothorax (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClassification of pneumothorax varies between institutions and guidelines - for example, a \u0022small\u0022 pneumothorax is defined as an interpleural distance of \u0026lt;2 cm by the British Thoracic Society, in a guideline which has been adopted by many Australian institutions. More often, it is patient symptoms and stability which will have value in guiding management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this pneumothorax is not a primary event and the patient is now symptom-free, she should be managed by \u003Cstrong\u003Eobservation in hospital\u003C/strong\u003E. More in line with current thinking, in the absence of any symptoms, this patient could also be considered for outpatient management and follow up. If that was the plan, she could be observed in the Emergency Department for a minimum of four hours and then a repeat chest X-ray performed. After observation, if she does not require any supplementary oxygen, was walking comfortably and the chest X-ray remained unchanged, she could be discharged with analgesia and written instructions as to what to do if her symptoms returned.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient still had symptoms, she might require hospitalisation and observation, or some form of drainage. The options would depend on the severity of her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration under CT guidance\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically necessary for a small, asymptomatic pneumothorax. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of an intercostal drain and admission to hospital\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for larger pneumothoraces or those causing significant symptoms or respiratory compromise. This patient is asymptomatic and stable, making this intervention unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EHeimlich valve \u003C/strong\u003Eis a one-way valve that is occluded during inspiration and held open during expiration allowing the egress of air from the pleural space. They can be used in the ambulatory management of a pneumothorax, however it is not the first-line approach for small, asymptomatic cases. Observation is preferred. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small pneumothoraces can usually be managed without any form of intervention."],"references":["Brown SGA, Ball EL, Perrin K, et al. Conservative versus Interventional Treatment for Spontaneous Pneumothorax. N Engl J Med 2020;382:405-15","Hallifax RJ, Roberts M, Russell N, Laskawiec-Szkonter M, Walker SP, Maskell NA, Rahman NM. Pneumothorax management: current state of practice in the UK. Respir Res. 2022 Feb 7;23(1):23. doi: 10.1186/s12931-022-01943-9. PMID: 35130917; PMCID: PMC8822726."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39711"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17880"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17881"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17880"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8e87c8a0-f65b-45d4-a57b-73f2b0e2cbc5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8e87c8a0-f65b-45d4-a57b-73f2b0e2cbc5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":423,"height":520}},{"type":"media","id":"17881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17881"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9ead0753-9a3a-4752-959d-917e57382d40.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9ead0753-9a3a-4752-959d-917e57382d40.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":423,"height":520}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39711"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T17:29:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T17:29:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54234"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou